WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.680 --> 00:00:01.960
LIV: Welcome, everybody.

00:00:01.960 --> 00:00:05.720
I'm Liv. I'm a cook here.

00:00:05.720 --> 00:00:10.870
And I'm just honored today to be
here with John Jeavons and

00:00:10.870 --> 00:00:13.710
to introduce him to you.

00:00:13.710 --> 00:00:17.760
If you care anything about what
your food tastes like, if

00:00:17.760 --> 00:00:21.720
you've dug a fork into food, you
really care about digging

00:00:21.720 --> 00:00:23.730
a fork into the Earth.

00:00:23.730 --> 00:00:28.570
And that's my whole connection
to all of this.

00:00:28.570 --> 00:00:32.670
You care about not just the
quality of food, but whether

00:00:32.670 --> 00:00:36.570
food is going to feed everybody
on this planet,

00:00:36.570 --> 00:00:40.930
which is one of the main
questions we have to answer

00:00:40.930 --> 00:00:42.790
these days--

00:00:42.790 --> 00:00:47.870
enough food, enough nutritious
food for everybody.

00:00:47.870 --> 00:00:54.970
When I was assigned to China as
a reporter a few years ago,

00:00:54.970 --> 00:00:59.930
for me, the most heartbreaking
thing I saw was in the

00:00:59.930 --> 00:01:05.034
countryside to see these dense
concentrations of farmers who

00:01:05.034 --> 00:01:08.250
were asked to leave the land
that they had farmed for

00:01:08.250 --> 00:01:14.930
generations and put in densely
populated living conditions no

00:01:14.930 --> 00:01:18.250
longer close to their
land because

00:01:18.250 --> 00:01:20.310
land was that precious.

00:01:20.310 --> 00:01:22.940
And the government wanted
to develop it.

00:01:22.940 --> 00:01:28.460
And here, I saw people who
knew the art of farming--

00:01:28.460 --> 00:01:31.100
and it is indeed an
art, growing food

00:01:31.100 --> 00:01:32.990
and growing it well--

00:01:32.990 --> 00:01:38.550
who had been through chemical
industrial farming who were

00:01:38.550 --> 00:01:41.400
told that some of the land that
they farm was now too

00:01:41.400 --> 00:01:48.200
toxic, over-fertilized, and
over-chemicalized for them to

00:01:48.200 --> 00:01:51.660
do any more, but who still in
their genes and just one

00:01:51.660 --> 00:01:56.500
generation back knew how to
grow food in mainly a

00:01:56.500 --> 00:01:58.730
sustainable way.

00:01:58.730 --> 00:02:01.570
And to me, I brought
that home with me.

00:02:01.570 --> 00:02:07.580
And to me, it's the overriding
question for this age

00:02:07.580 --> 00:02:09.270
and for all of us.

00:02:09.270 --> 00:02:12.890
So from the time I was an
immigrant that arrived in this

00:02:12.890 --> 00:02:18.220
country, I'd heard about
double digging.

00:02:18.220 --> 00:02:20.670
I'd heard about biointensive.

00:02:20.670 --> 00:02:25.680
And today, for me to meet John
and realize that he is this

00:02:25.680 --> 00:02:32.170
complete visionary who isn't
just a farmer, but is thinking

00:02:32.170 --> 00:02:35.980
about food for all of us and for
the future of this planet

00:02:35.980 --> 00:02:37.480
is indeed an honor.

00:02:37.480 --> 00:02:40.604
So please welcome John.

00:02:40.604 --> 00:02:41.566
[APPLAUSE]

00:02:41.566 --> 00:02:49.630
JOHN JEAVONS: Thank
you, Liv. Take the

00:02:49.630 --> 00:02:51.440
lights down on the screen.

00:02:51.440 --> 00:02:52.690
They got me lit.

00:02:55.150 --> 00:02:57.880
Before we begin, I'd
like to make one

00:02:57.880 --> 00:03:00.490
reflection to set the tone.

00:03:00.490 --> 00:03:04.620
What Liz said about China in
some way reminded me of it.

00:03:04.620 --> 00:03:08.960
In 1995, we had an intern come
and train with us in Northern

00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:11.640
California for six months.

00:03:11.640 --> 00:03:15.860
And he shared with me that the
cost of farmable soil in

00:03:15.860 --> 00:03:20.020
Monterey, Mexico,
was $4 a pound.

00:03:20.020 --> 00:03:24.100
Do you realize that gasoline
only costs $50 a pound

00:03:24.100 --> 00:03:27.570
currently at the pump?

00:03:27.570 --> 00:03:28.190
$50.

00:03:28.190 --> 00:03:29.060
Oh, there we go again.

00:03:29.060 --> 00:03:30.420
We're going to have
to redo this one.

00:03:32.970 --> 00:03:37.110
Do you realize that in Monterey,
Mexico, that

00:03:37.110 --> 00:03:40.440
farmable soil, if you go to
purchase it, costs $4 a pound,

00:03:40.440 --> 00:03:45.630
where gasoline at the pumps
today costs $0.50 a pound.

00:03:45.630 --> 00:03:47.750
So they have their
priorities right.

00:03:47.750 --> 00:03:50.630
They realize the preciousness
of the soil.

00:03:50.630 --> 00:03:54.890
And they realize that the soil
is worth eight times gasoline.

00:03:54.890 --> 00:03:55.980
Wow.

00:03:55.980 --> 00:03:58.510
That's really hard to wrap our
minds around, I think.

00:03:58.510 --> 00:04:00.960
Even for me, it is, and
I've been working

00:04:00.960 --> 00:04:02.815
with this for 41 years.

00:04:02.815 --> 00:04:10.620
So now let's go and look at our
presentation for today,

00:04:10.620 --> 00:04:12.115
Food for the Future Now.

00:04:15.100 --> 00:04:19.220
To know, challenge, and hope.

00:04:19.220 --> 00:04:22.730
To feel, relieved
and empowered.

00:04:22.730 --> 00:04:25.365
And to do, act where you are.

00:04:30.270 --> 00:04:34.340
Creating a new and
better world.

00:04:34.340 --> 00:04:36.020
Creating a new and
better world.

00:04:36.020 --> 00:04:42.260
This is going to be the only
thing we need to focus on.

00:04:42.260 --> 00:04:45.450
The joy of the process, it's
really a lot of fun.

00:04:45.450 --> 00:04:48.520
You can see the happiness
in my daughter's face.

00:04:48.520 --> 00:04:51.890
And even manual food-raising,
which is really

00:04:51.890 --> 00:04:54.040
skill-intensive, not

00:04:54.040 --> 00:04:58.730
work-intensive, is a lot of fun.

00:04:58.730 --> 00:05:01.640
The Earth needs our help now.

00:05:01.640 --> 00:05:03.710
You probably know
that already.

00:05:03.710 --> 00:05:06.650
But this is literally the Earth
that's underneath our

00:05:06.650 --> 00:05:11.310
feet needs our help right now.

00:05:11.310 --> 00:05:14.760
Let's grow soil.

00:05:14.760 --> 00:05:16.430
It's not about farming it.

00:05:16.430 --> 00:05:19.240
It's about growing it.

00:05:19.240 --> 00:05:22.250
Every time we eat a pound of
food grown with regular

00:05:22.250 --> 00:05:26.560
food-raising practices, an
average of 6 pounds in the

00:05:26.560 --> 00:05:29.400
United States, 12 pounds in
developing countries, where

00:05:29.400 --> 00:05:33.960
90% of the world's people live,
and 18 pounds in China,

00:05:33.960 --> 00:05:39.590
where 20% of the world's people
live, and 24 pounds of

00:05:39.590 --> 00:05:44.620
farmable soil in California are
lost due to wind and water

00:05:44.620 --> 00:05:49.530
erosion because of the types
of practices being used.

00:05:49.530 --> 00:05:53.710
In contrast, over here on
the right, you can see

00:05:53.710 --> 00:05:58.260
Biointensive Sustainable
Mini-Farming has the capacity

00:05:58.260 --> 00:06:03.200
to build, to grow, to create
up to 20 pounds of farmable

00:06:03.200 --> 00:06:06.090
soil per pound of food eaten--

00:06:06.090 --> 00:06:11.770
not deplete 6 to 24 pounds per
pound of food eaten, but to

00:06:11.770 --> 00:06:17.390
build up to 20 pounds of
farmable soil, soil we need to

00:06:17.390 --> 00:06:19.680
feed people.

00:06:19.680 --> 00:06:23.180
I don't think anyone realizes
the number of people that are

00:06:23.180 --> 00:06:24.810
born each day, really.

00:06:24.810 --> 00:06:28.030
It's 216,000 people net.

00:06:28.030 --> 00:06:31.610
That's births less deaths.

00:06:31.610 --> 00:06:36.370
It's like Motel 6, and the
light's on all the time.

00:06:36.370 --> 00:06:38.310
This is enough to
repopulate San

00:06:38.310 --> 00:06:41.040
Francisco every three days.

00:06:41.040 --> 00:06:41.740
Wow.

00:06:41.740 --> 00:06:44.030
Costa Rica every 17.

00:06:44.030 --> 00:06:48.780
Mexico City, the second largest
city in the world, 3.5

00:06:48.780 --> 00:06:50.400
times a year.

00:06:50.400 --> 00:06:55.360
And Beijing, China,
8.6 times a year.

00:06:55.360 --> 00:06:57.990
What does this mean?

00:06:57.990 --> 00:06:58.950
It means--

00:06:58.950 --> 00:07:00.790
and this is even more
important than those

00:07:00.790 --> 00:07:02.860
population statistics--

00:07:02.860 --> 00:07:06.950
it means that 34,000 additional
acres of farmable

00:07:06.950 --> 00:07:12.830
soil need to be found or built
daily to feed these people.

00:07:12.830 --> 00:07:16.020
It's not happening.

00:07:16.020 --> 00:07:20.710
It's probable that organic
farming indirectly results in

00:07:20.710 --> 00:07:23.780
the loss of three to five and
a quarter pounds of farmable

00:07:23.780 --> 00:07:28.750
soil per pound of food eaten
because of the needs of inputs

00:07:28.750 --> 00:07:32.940
in the form of compost, manure,
and organic fertilizer

00:07:32.940 --> 00:07:35.400
which are taken from
other soils.

00:07:35.400 --> 00:07:38.440
So we may have our perfect
organic farm.

00:07:38.440 --> 00:07:41.080
But we're depleting a
soil somewhere else

00:07:41.080 --> 00:07:42.780
in order to do it.

00:07:42.780 --> 00:07:44.170
We don't need to.

00:07:44.170 --> 00:07:48.860
But the pattern we're
using now does.

00:07:48.860 --> 00:07:51.110
Organic farming is
a good start.

00:07:51.110 --> 00:07:54.630
It's a great start.

00:07:54.630 --> 00:07:57.780
It's a major positive step
towards more sustainable

00:07:57.780 --> 00:07:58.440
agriculture.

00:07:58.440 --> 00:08:00.800
Yet, we need to take
at least three

00:08:00.800 --> 00:08:04.760
more major steps forward.

00:08:04.760 --> 00:08:06.345
We need to go beyond organic.

00:08:09.270 --> 00:08:11.830
The planet is becoming
increasingly urbanized.

00:08:11.830 --> 00:08:16.310
Something that's incredible is
India's already 91% urban,

00:08:16.310 --> 00:08:19.320
China 90% urban.

00:08:19.320 --> 00:08:21.090
That's 40% of the world's

00:08:21.090 --> 00:08:24.400
population virtually urbanized.

00:08:24.400 --> 00:08:27.060
One of the results of this
urbanization is that we're

00:08:27.060 --> 00:08:29.940
losing our farming literacy.

00:08:29.940 --> 00:08:31.730
We don't really know
how to farm.

00:08:34.480 --> 00:08:38.240
As a result of all these
factors, agriculture, as it

00:08:38.240 --> 00:08:43.260
is, population growth, the
loss of our farming skill

00:08:43.260 --> 00:08:46.180
base, most of the world's
soils have become

00:08:46.180 --> 00:08:52.360
significantly demineralized,
compacted, and contain little

00:08:52.360 --> 00:08:54.880
organic matter unless all these

00:08:54.880 --> 00:08:56.130
elements have been imported.

00:09:00.630 --> 00:09:04.020
This isn't a pretty picture.

00:09:04.020 --> 00:09:07.990
Though, I think the art
here is very pretty.

00:09:07.990 --> 00:09:11.110
You can make a case that the
entire planet may be

00:09:11.110 --> 00:09:18.830
desertified in as little
as 69 years.

00:09:18.830 --> 00:09:21.590
I'm 70 years old.

00:09:21.590 --> 00:09:26.280
That's in less time than I've
been here on the planet.

00:09:26.280 --> 00:09:27.850
| don't know how long
you've been here.

00:09:27.850 --> 00:09:31.020
But that's a short time.

00:09:31.020 --> 00:09:32.670
What to do?

00:09:32.670 --> 00:09:35.960
We need to make farming truly
sustainable on as much of a

00:09:35.960 --> 00:09:39.440
closed system basis
as possible.

00:09:39.440 --> 00:09:41.480
It is possible.

00:09:41.480 --> 00:09:44.210
We need to grow our own organic
matter inputs on the

00:09:44.210 --> 00:09:47.470
soil we cultivate and recycle
all the nutrients--

00:09:47.470 --> 00:09:48.790
all the nutrients--

00:09:48.790 --> 00:09:51.850
contained in the crops we
grow back into the soil.

00:09:54.740 --> 00:09:58.230
The United Nations Food and
Agriculture Organization has

00:09:58.230 --> 00:10:02.730
noted that 13 years from
now, in the year 2025--

00:10:02.730 --> 00:10:05.340
that's soon--

00:10:05.340 --> 00:10:11.620
about 2/3 of the world's people,
5 billion people, will

00:10:11.620 --> 00:10:14.540
probably not have sufficient
water available for food

00:10:14.540 --> 00:10:16.680
growing to live a life
with reasonable

00:10:16.680 --> 00:10:19.100
nutrition if at all.

00:10:26.690 --> 00:10:29.690
We don't have to wait for
2025 for that to happen.

00:10:29.690 --> 00:10:32.820
We're going to see that
happening in just three years,

00:10:32.820 --> 00:10:35.190
the effect of this.

00:10:35.190 --> 00:10:39.510
This means a situation of peak
water and peak food.

00:10:39.510 --> 00:10:43.580
70% to 80% of all the water used
by people in the world is

00:10:43.580 --> 00:10:45.055
utilized in food production.

00:10:48.680 --> 00:10:50.090
There is some hope.

00:10:50.090 --> 00:10:53.180
We'll get to that soon.

00:10:53.180 --> 00:10:56.630
You can also make a case that
as little as 49 years of

00:10:56.630 --> 00:11:00.600
farmable soil remains
on the Earth.

00:11:00.600 --> 00:11:05.010
This is partly because as the
soil quality is depleted, the

00:11:05.010 --> 00:11:09.170
rate of depletion increases
more rapidly.

00:11:09.170 --> 00:11:13.020
So we have a situation of
peak farmable soil.

00:11:13.020 --> 00:11:14.270
And it's here now.

00:11:18.800 --> 00:11:24.130
There's also a major different
kind of peak energy crisis.

00:11:24.130 --> 00:11:27.840
The peak energy crisis really
is between these two points

00:11:27.840 --> 00:11:30.650
and these two points--

00:11:30.650 --> 00:11:34.710
our will, the will to face
these things and make a

00:11:34.710 --> 00:11:36.730
positive difference.

00:11:36.730 --> 00:11:39.300
And I wouldn't tell you these
things if we couldn't make a

00:11:39.300 --> 00:11:40.550
positive difference.

00:11:44.900 --> 00:11:49.630
Feed your dreams and your
fears will starve.

00:11:49.630 --> 00:11:52.850
So in the future, as you begin
to be overwhelmed by

00:11:52.850 --> 00:11:56.420
challenges, and there's a good
chance that we will all have

00:11:56.420 --> 00:11:59.440
that feeling some of the time,
feed your dreams. And you'll

00:11:59.440 --> 00:12:02.950
find that the dream that you're
envisioning will begin

00:12:02.950 --> 00:12:09.030
to manifest.

00:12:09.030 --> 00:12:11.940
And the reason that we can dream
these dreams is because

00:12:11.940 --> 00:12:13.996
there are realistic solutions.

00:12:16.910 --> 00:12:19.670
We need to utilize our
skillful will.

00:12:19.670 --> 00:12:22.720
There are psychologists who
have studied the different

00:12:22.720 --> 00:12:26.740
forms of will that we have. And
the most important one is

00:12:26.740 --> 00:12:31.900
skillful will, the ability to
make and fulfill our choices

00:12:31.900 --> 00:12:36.360
with the greatest efficiency
and least effort necessary.

00:12:36.360 --> 00:12:39.740
I think Google is dedicated
to this concept.

00:12:44.140 --> 00:12:47.180
What we need is a
transformational paradigm

00:12:47.180 --> 00:12:50.270
throughout many areas, including
food-raising.

00:12:53.540 --> 00:12:58.020
Growing food was actually
the original green.

00:12:58.020 --> 00:12:59.315
And it can be again.

00:13:01.830 --> 00:13:06.930
In fact, 10,000 years ago--

00:13:06.930 --> 00:13:09.430
this is unbelievable if
you really sink into

00:13:09.430 --> 00:13:11.210
this and feel it.

00:13:11.210 --> 00:13:12.630
This next thing is just totally

00:13:12.630 --> 00:13:15.650
unbelievable and wonderful.

00:13:15.650 --> 00:13:19.460
10,000 years ago, early Stone
Age farmers raised 100% of

00:13:19.460 --> 00:13:23.020
their calories per person with
just 20 hours of labor

00:13:23.020 --> 00:13:28.460
annually, growing the
first spelt wheat.

00:13:28.460 --> 00:13:31.410
These people were farming
literate.

00:13:31.410 --> 00:13:37.520
I often give participants in
our workshop a handicap, a

00:13:37.520 --> 00:13:39.480
fivefold handicap.

00:13:39.480 --> 00:13:42.430
And I challenge them to learn
how to grow all their food in

00:13:42.430 --> 00:13:47.730
100 hours a year during the
following three years.

00:13:47.730 --> 00:13:49.650
We really can do it.

00:13:49.650 --> 00:13:53.420
We don't believe we can, but
that's where the problem is,

00:13:53.420 --> 00:13:54.845
here and here.

00:13:58.460 --> 00:14:05.030
In 1911, China grew complete
diets on 3,600 square feet.

00:14:05.030 --> 00:14:08.410
And China, Japan, and Korea used
biologically-intensive

00:14:08.410 --> 00:14:15.980
farming successfully for four
millennia until the 1950s when

00:14:15.980 --> 00:14:19.500
current practices began
to be adopted.

00:14:19.500 --> 00:14:23.670
The Chinese used to call their
farmers living libraries.

00:14:23.670 --> 00:14:26.880
And if you want to read about
this type of farming, there's

00:14:26.880 --> 00:14:31.720
a book out by F.H. King called
Farmers of Forty Centuries.

00:14:31.720 --> 00:14:33.770
I recommend you read it.

00:14:33.770 --> 00:14:38.490
It's published by Dover Press,
and it's not expensive.

00:14:38.490 --> 00:14:41.580
In the Philippines, the
illiterate Hanunoo Stone Age

00:14:41.580 --> 00:14:46.460
culture have a 200-crop,
5-year rotation with 40

00:14:46.460 --> 00:14:49.550
varieties of rice
grown annually.

00:14:49.550 --> 00:14:54.350
So no matter what the climate,
hot, cold, wet, or dry, they

00:14:54.350 --> 00:14:57.630
achieve a sufficient quantity
of calories.

00:14:57.630 --> 00:14:59.290
They are living libraries too.

00:15:02.900 --> 00:15:05.810
There are no agricultural
universities that I know of in

00:15:05.810 --> 00:15:09.080
the world that have any kind of
rotation system that's as

00:15:09.080 --> 00:15:14.310
sophisticated, or as complex,
and uses so many varieties as

00:15:14.310 --> 00:15:16.340
this one does.

00:15:16.340 --> 00:15:18.090
And these people don't
know how to read

00:15:18.090 --> 00:15:20.840
and don't use computers.

00:15:20.840 --> 00:15:22.360
Oh my god.

00:15:22.360 --> 00:15:26.040
And it's even worse because they
spend 80% of their table

00:15:26.040 --> 00:15:30.720
conversation at meals talking
about farming.

00:15:30.720 --> 00:15:33.130
And their children, if they were
in inner city schools,

00:15:33.130 --> 00:15:35.570
you'd have to disassociate
yourself from them because

00:15:35.570 --> 00:15:36.820
they play farmer.

00:15:44.040 --> 00:15:46.870
When other cultures around them
were fading, the Mayan

00:15:46.870 --> 00:15:48.800
culture thrived with
neighborhood--

00:15:48.800 --> 00:15:50.900
there's documentation
on this--

00:15:50.900 --> 00:15:52.860
neighborhood
biologically-intensive

00:15:52.860 --> 00:15:54.950
food-raising.

00:15:54.950 --> 00:15:59.970
Why did the Mayan culture
eventually dissipate?

00:15:59.970 --> 00:16:00.750
No one knows.

00:16:00.750 --> 00:16:02.880
There's maybe five or
six possibilities.

00:16:02.880 --> 00:16:05.850
But one of them no
one has listed.

00:16:05.850 --> 00:16:11.500
They may not have been farming
with biological intensivity in

00:16:11.500 --> 00:16:13.700
a sustainable way.

00:16:13.700 --> 00:16:17.250
You can deplete your soil really
fast if you don't do it

00:16:17.250 --> 00:16:19.620
sustainably.

00:16:19.620 --> 00:16:22.230
Biosphere II, where they locked
six people up in a

00:16:22.230 --> 00:16:27.180
two-acre greenhouse for two
years, grew complete diets on

00:16:27.180 --> 00:16:29.530
about 3,300 square feet with

00:16:29.530 --> 00:16:32.520
biologically-intensive practices.

00:16:32.520 --> 00:16:38.450
In fact, one of our interns
trained the basis for that

00:16:38.450 --> 00:16:39.740
food-raising.

