00:24:01.700 --> 00:24:05.070
We've discovered that this
method, Grow Biointensive

00:24:05.070 --> 00:24:08.120
Sustainable Mini-Farming, has
the capacity to produce higher

00:24:08.120 --> 00:24:12.320
yields and increased income per
unit of area and use as

00:24:12.320 --> 00:24:15.820
little as 33% to
12% the water.

00:24:15.820 --> 00:24:19.930
We've been down as low
as 3% the water.

00:24:19.930 --> 00:24:24.000
Use as little as 50% to 100%
less purchased nutrient and

00:24:24.000 --> 00:24:26.910
organic fertilizer form.

00:24:26.910 --> 00:24:34.000
And use as little as 6% to 1%
the energy in all forms,

00:24:34.000 --> 00:24:37.710
compared with practices normally
used per pound of

00:24:37.710 --> 00:24:38.960
food produced.

00:24:41.060 --> 00:24:43.490
Grow Biointensive builds soil.

00:24:43.490 --> 00:24:46.020
According to a master's thesis
from the University of

00:24:46.020 --> 00:24:49.620
California at Berkeley in the
soil science department there,

00:24:49.620 --> 00:24:53.290
Grow Biointensive has the
capacity to build soil up to

00:24:53.290 --> 00:24:56.860
60 times more rapidly
than in nature.

00:24:56.860 --> 00:24:58.110
What does this mean?

00:25:00.510 --> 00:25:04.270
Up to six inches of farmable
soil can be built in as little

00:25:04.270 --> 00:25:06.730
as 50 years.

00:25:06.730 --> 00:25:10.520
Remember earlier I noted that
in as little as 49 years,

00:25:10.520 --> 00:25:14.600
there might be no farmable
soil left.

00:25:14.600 --> 00:25:18.180
So we might as well begin
now and avoid the rush.

00:25:18.180 --> 00:25:21.420
We could be in time.

00:25:21.420 --> 00:25:23.980
On the average around the
world and in the US, it

00:25:23.980 --> 00:25:28.010
doesn't take 50 years to build
up 6 inches of farmable soil,

00:25:28.010 --> 00:25:31.150
the depth of soil you need
in order to grow food.

00:25:31.150 --> 00:25:34.250
It takes 3,000 years
to do this.

00:25:34.250 --> 00:25:38.700
And in California, because
of the natural geologic

00:25:38.700 --> 00:25:42.330
formation, the climate, and
other factors, it takes 12,000

00:25:42.330 --> 00:25:47.910
years to build up 6 inches
of farmable soil.

00:25:47.910 --> 00:25:52.390
Do you realize that the 3,000
years of farmable soil that

00:25:52.390 --> 00:25:57.120
we've built up in the United
States, that we've depleted

00:25:57.120 --> 00:26:02.320
75% of it in the
last 250 years?

00:26:02.320 --> 00:26:07.580
We depleted 2,250 years'
worth in 250 years.

00:26:07.580 --> 00:26:12.390
And the rate at which it's being
depleted is increasing.

00:26:12.390 --> 00:26:15.780
We don't have to do that.

00:26:15.780 --> 00:26:18.430
With Grow Biointensive higher
yields plus a better

00:26:18.430 --> 00:26:22.420
understanding of nutrition from
a farming point of view,

00:26:22.420 --> 00:26:26.410
it's possible to grow diets plus
all the compost materials

00:26:26.410 --> 00:26:30.540
needed for sustainable soil
fertility on as little as

00:26:30.540 --> 00:26:39.170
4,000, 2,500, 1,800, or even
1,000 square feet or less

00:26:39.170 --> 00:26:40.420
depending on the diet.

00:26:45.030 --> 00:26:48.050
You could even do it
in the yard on your

00:26:48.050 --> 00:26:50.530
suburban home lot.

00:26:50.530 --> 00:26:55.810
Frightening, the responsibility
is.

00:26:55.810 --> 00:26:57.950
It's true that the foods
eaten are different.

00:26:57.950 --> 00:27:02.720
But all nourishment for world
standards is met in all of

00:27:02.720 --> 00:27:04.430
these small diets.

00:27:04.430 --> 00:27:06.790
How does Grow Biointensive
do this?

00:27:06.790 --> 00:27:08.780
Deep soil structure
creation for

00:27:08.780 --> 00:27:12.880
quadruple nutrient cycling.

00:27:12.880 --> 00:27:15.270
Compost for microbe nutrition.

00:27:15.270 --> 00:27:19.960
Soil, water retention, and soil
antibiotic development.

00:27:19.960 --> 00:27:22.330
Plants don't get sick if you
have enough microbes in the

00:27:22.330 --> 00:27:25.450
soil because they have their own
pharmaceutical thing going

00:27:25.450 --> 00:27:27.940
on down there to keep
the plants healthy.

00:27:27.940 --> 00:27:32.130
And if the plants are healthy,
insects don't come because the

00:27:32.130 --> 00:27:37.050
amino acid mix in the plant
tissue is such that the

00:27:37.050 --> 00:27:38.590
insects are not interested.

00:27:38.590 --> 00:27:42.370
But a sick plant, the amino
acid mix changes.

00:27:42.370 --> 00:27:47.290
And the signal goes out to the
insects, and they come for

00:27:47.290 --> 00:27:49.310
their feast.

00:27:49.310 --> 00:27:52.730
Close plant spacing for improved
plant environment and

00:27:52.730 --> 00:27:54.820
water conservation.

00:27:54.820 --> 00:27:57.880
Companion planting, putting
plants together that like each

00:27:57.880 --> 00:27:59.770
other and stimulate
each other--

00:27:59.770 --> 00:28:04.210
like the people you choose for
your parties or your dinners--

00:28:04.210 --> 00:28:08.640
for crop enhancement and
pest minimization.

00:28:08.640 --> 00:28:12.900
60% growing area in compost and
calorie crops that produce

00:28:12.900 --> 00:28:16.490
large amount of compost
materials, plus a significant

00:28:16.490 --> 00:28:18.780
quantity of calories,
such as wheat,

00:28:18.780 --> 00:28:21.370
oats, corn, and amaranth.

00:28:21.370 --> 00:28:24.220
But there are many others.

00:28:24.220 --> 00:28:27.610
30% of our growing area in
special root crops-- and in a

00:28:27.610 --> 00:28:30.410
moment, you'll see how important
that is, it's very

00:28:30.410 --> 00:28:31.840
important--

00:28:31.840 --> 00:28:40.930
such as potatoes, garlic, and
leeks that can produce 5 to 20

00:28:40.930 --> 00:28:43.960
times the calories per unit
of area per unit of time.

00:28:48.800 --> 00:28:52.590
Using easily available seeds.

00:28:52.590 --> 00:28:54.100
And using the whole system.

00:28:54.100 --> 00:28:57.780
It doesn't work well if only
some of its elements are used.

00:28:57.780 --> 00:28:59.870
If you prepare the soil
shallowly and put all the

00:28:59.870 --> 00:29:03.370
plants close together,
you stress the soil.

00:29:03.370 --> 00:29:07.610
And the system may even
become unsustainable.

00:29:07.610 --> 00:29:12.090
The solution to sustainable
agriculture isn't the system.

00:29:12.090 --> 00:29:16.170
It's you, and me, and
how we use it.

00:29:16.170 --> 00:29:20.230
Taking into account all the
preceding, scarcity can be

00:29:20.230 --> 00:29:23.770
transformed into abundance.

00:29:23.770 --> 00:29:27.250
The transformation of the
situations of peak water, peak

00:29:27.250 --> 00:29:30.590
farming energy, and peak
farmable soil into situations

00:29:30.590 --> 00:29:33.710
of more than enough.

00:29:33.710 --> 00:29:36.110
We don't need to be facing
the scarcity that

00:29:36.110 --> 00:29:38.380
we're looking at globally.

00:29:38.380 --> 00:29:40.290
We can be looking at
abundance instead.

00:29:44.170 --> 00:29:46.560
In a way, it's not all
that challenging.

00:29:46.560 --> 00:29:49.140
You may feel overwhelmed
right now.

00:29:49.140 --> 00:29:53.640
But let's go to a quote from
Voltaire in his book Candide,

00:29:53.640 --> 00:29:55.910
on the last page.

00:29:55.910 --> 00:30:01.420
Candide says, "The whole world
is a garden, and what a

00:30:01.420 --> 00:30:04.720
wonderful place it would be if
each one of us just took care

00:30:04.720 --> 00:30:08.070
of our part of the Earth,
our garden."

00:30:08.070 --> 00:30:09.620
It's not complicated.

00:30:09.620 --> 00:30:11.730
It's simple.

00:30:11.730 --> 00:30:13.900
It's not someone else who
needs to take the

00:30:13.900 --> 00:30:15.940
responsibility.

00:30:15.940 --> 00:30:16.560
We can.

00:30:16.560 --> 00:30:20.150
And it's a pleasurable
responsibility.

00:30:20.150 --> 00:30:25.140
Gandhi, "To forget how to dig
the Earth and tend the soil is

00:30:25.140 --> 00:30:31.620
to forget oneself." Grow
Biointensive is

00:30:31.620 --> 00:30:34.220
skill-intensive, rather
than labor-intensive.

00:30:34.220 --> 00:30:37.960
As you can see here, there's as
many lettuces in the upper

00:30:37.960 --> 00:30:40.650
area as in the lower area.

00:30:40.650 --> 00:30:43.190
The amount of work, if you
know how to Aikido double

00:30:43.190 --> 00:30:45.990
dig-- which actually, you
don't do the work.

00:30:45.990 --> 00:30:49.340
Gravity does the work.

00:30:49.340 --> 00:30:53.140
The amount of energy it takes
to double dig that in a very

00:30:53.140 --> 00:31:03.010
quiet, simple, easy way is the
same amount of energy that it

00:31:03.010 --> 00:31:07.940
is to single dig two
of those row areas.

00:31:07.940 --> 00:31:09.100
So it's less work.

00:31:09.100 --> 00:31:10.050
It's less water.

00:31:10.050 --> 00:31:11.080
It's less weeding.

00:31:11.080 --> 00:31:16.230
It's less compost. It's less
nutrients in organic

00:31:16.230 --> 00:31:17.480
fertilizer form.

00:31:17.480 --> 00:31:18.850
It's skill-intensive.

00:31:18.850 --> 00:31:20.240
Don't work harder.

00:31:20.240 --> 00:31:22.490
Think smarter.

00:31:22.490 --> 00:31:23.730
Small is bountiful.

00:31:23.730 --> 00:31:27.510
And there truly are economies
of small scale.

00:31:27.510 --> 00:31:30.300
Remember how much less water
and nutrient we use?

00:31:30.300 --> 00:31:33.500
Those are economies
of small scale.

00:31:33.500 --> 00:31:36.870
And we need to become
farming literate.

00:31:39.740 --> 00:31:42.240
So what does this mean for
us in our own backyards?

00:31:42.240 --> 00:31:45.060
And what does this mean
for our communities?

00:31:45.060 --> 00:31:47.820
Assuming intermediate Grow
Biointensive yields, one

00:31:47.820 --> 00:31:51.070
mature apple tree can produce
one pound of apples for each

00:31:51.070 --> 00:31:54.760
day in the year for three
and a quarter people.

00:31:54.760 --> 00:31:57.910
In addition, you can graft 9
additional varieties on the

00:31:57.910 --> 00:32:02.240
tree for a total of 10
producing varieties.

00:32:02.240 --> 00:32:05.480
Luther Burbank had 30 varieties
of plums grafted on

00:32:05.480 --> 00:32:07.710
one plum tree in Santa
Rosa, California.

00:32:07.710 --> 00:32:10.730
You can go still see the tree.

00:32:10.730 --> 00:32:14.420
It only has 10 varieties on it
now because they didn't want

00:32:14.420 --> 00:32:16.040
to keep up with that
complexity.

00:32:16.040 --> 00:32:18.690
But wouldn't it be wonderful
to go have that kind of a

00:32:18.690 --> 00:32:20.060
choice right at home?

00:32:23.120 --> 00:32:26.270
Also assuming intermediate Grow
Biointensive yields, you

00:32:26.270 --> 00:32:28.950
can grow one 1-pound loaf of
bread for each week in the

00:32:28.950 --> 00:32:35.510
year in just 300 square feet of
wheat, two good-sized bowls

00:32:35.510 --> 00:32:39.090
of oatmeal per week in another
300 square feet

00:32:39.090 --> 00:32:41.380
using hulless oats.

00:32:41.380 --> 00:32:44.970
You can experience that
primordial waves of grain

00:32:44.970 --> 00:32:49.140
feeling right where you are.

00:32:49.140 --> 00:32:50.850
Now all crops are not equal.

00:32:50.850 --> 00:32:52.040
This is really important.

00:32:52.040 --> 00:32:54.240
And if you get the new edition
of How to Grow More

00:32:54.240 --> 00:32:59.260
Vegetables, the last three
pages also of the compost

00:32:59.260 --> 00:33:04.200
chapter describe how all
compost is not equal.

00:33:04.200 --> 00:33:08.210
Here, what we're going to see
is we have wheat, which is a

00:33:08.210 --> 00:33:11.330
winter grain crop.

00:33:11.330 --> 00:33:17.430
And the calories produced per
month set our index of one

00:33:17.430 --> 00:33:19.630
unit of productivity.

00:33:19.630 --> 00:33:25.260
If instead we use flour corn,
which is a summer seed crop,

00:33:25.260 --> 00:33:27.630
we have five times the
productivity and

00:33:27.630 --> 00:33:29.920
calories per month.

00:33:29.920 --> 00:33:33.780
And if instead we use potatoes,
a 65-day maturing

00:33:33.780 --> 00:33:38.100
variety, we get nineteen times
the calories per month per

00:33:38.100 --> 00:33:40.380
unit of area.

00:33:40.380 --> 00:33:41.630
Powerful.

00:33:43.310 --> 00:33:46.640
If you read the material on
compost, you'll find that

00:33:46.640 --> 00:33:49.270
instead of just having a bucket
of compost that you

00:33:49.270 --> 00:33:53.110
dump into an area where you're
growing, that bucket of

00:33:53.110 --> 00:33:57.320
compost can be one unit of
compost power, two units of

00:33:57.320 --> 00:34:02.940
compost power, and up to eight
units of compost power.

00:34:02.940 --> 00:34:08.000
This is what 41 years of
research, teaching, and, most

00:34:08.000 --> 00:34:12.360
important, learning by Ecology
Action is making possible for

00:34:12.360 --> 00:34:16.969
everyone in the world
on a simple basis.

00:34:16.969 --> 00:34:20.710
But the final question really
is, what kind of future do you

00:34:20.710 --> 00:34:22.770
want to create?

