00:42:27.310 --> 00:42:29.090
JOHN JEAVONS: Well, when we
began at the Stanford

00:42:29.090 --> 00:42:33.730
University Industrial Park,
all the top soil had been

00:42:33.730 --> 00:42:38.800
scraped off of the area that
was donated to us.

00:42:38.800 --> 00:42:41.290
And all of the subsoil had
been scraped off in the

00:42:41.290 --> 00:42:43.660
construction process.

00:42:43.660 --> 00:42:48.300
So we were growing our crops
in a mollisol clay that

00:42:48.300 --> 00:42:52.090
normally takes at least 500
years in nature to make one

00:42:52.090 --> 00:42:53.910
inch of farmable soil out of.

00:42:53.910 --> 00:42:56.730
And we got fairly good results
to begin with.

00:42:56.730 --> 00:42:59.740
But you get better results
over time.

00:42:59.740 --> 00:43:02.820
One thing that I want everyone
to understand is to build up a

00:43:02.820 --> 00:43:07.670
soil in a temperate zone and to
have a good soil, you need

00:43:07.670 --> 00:43:13.320
4% to 6% organic matter
in the soil.

00:43:13.320 --> 00:43:17.950
Most of the world's soils are
only 1% organic matter.

00:43:17.950 --> 00:43:22.080
And you can only, in a stable
way, build up a soil in

00:43:22.080 --> 00:43:26.010
organic matter 1/20
of 1% a year.

00:43:26.010 --> 00:43:31.820
So to build up from 1% organic
matter soil to 4%, the minimum

00:43:31.820 --> 00:43:34.260
to have a really good
soil, it's going

00:43:34.260 --> 00:43:38.610
to take us 60 years.

00:43:38.610 --> 00:43:43.570
So it involves a responsibility,
a commitment,

00:43:43.570 --> 00:43:44.610
and a relationship.

00:43:44.610 --> 00:43:47.110
We know how difficult
relationships are.

00:43:47.110 --> 00:43:51.360
But this one's with the soil
and with the planet.

00:43:51.360 --> 00:43:53.890
And to be a farmer of the
future, what we're going to

00:43:53.890 --> 00:43:56.130
have to do-- this is going
to be really hard because

00:43:56.130 --> 00:43:58.040
