00:48:14.740 --> 00:48:16.750
They're crunchy.

00:48:16.750 --> 00:48:19.290
But they're really
water efficient.

00:48:19.290 --> 00:48:22.520
There are a number of crops in
the world in the grain seed

00:48:22.520 --> 00:48:25.100
area that are called C4 crops.

00:48:25.100 --> 00:48:27.510
They have a special
genetic pathway.

00:48:27.510 --> 00:48:31.620
And this enables them to produce
more calories and more

00:48:31.620 --> 00:48:34.110
carbon with less water.

00:48:34.110 --> 00:48:38.530
But I'll give you an idea of
what this method that we're

00:48:38.530 --> 00:48:41.900
using and learning about does.

00:48:41.900 --> 00:48:45.340
In the Stanford Industrial Park,
when we began in 1972 in

00:48:45.340 --> 00:48:49.440
Santa Clara County, where you
are right now, they were using

00:48:49.440 --> 00:48:53.570
20 gallons of water for 100
square feet per day in

00:48:53.570 --> 00:48:55.300
agriculture.

00:48:55.300 --> 00:48:58.270
When we began, we were too.

00:48:58.270 --> 00:49:04.260
After five years, we were down
to 10 gallons of water per 100

00:49:04.260 --> 00:49:05.400
square feet per day.

00:49:05.400 --> 00:49:10.550
And after six, we were down
to 8 gallons of water.

00:49:10.550 --> 00:49:14.110
But the yields that we
were getting were two

00:49:14.110 --> 00:49:16.100
to five times higher.

00:49:16.100 --> 00:49:19.650
So really, we would end up
using, to make a long story

00:49:19.650 --> 00:49:24.180
short, 1/8 the water per pound
of vegetable produced.

00:49:24.180 --> 00:49:25.360
Now how do we do this?

00:49:25.360 --> 00:49:27.350
And that's what you're asking.

00:49:27.350 --> 00:49:28.930
First of all, we have
a new booklet out.

00:49:28.930 --> 00:49:36.335
It's called booklet 35.

00:49:36.335 --> 00:49:40.510
It's name is "Growing More Food
with Less Water." So I'll

00:49:40.510 --> 00:49:44.800
tell you the three ways that
this method enables you to use

00:49:44.800 --> 00:49:46.230
so much less water.

00:49:46.230 --> 00:49:49.690
What it means is that those
people, the 5 billion people

00:49:49.690 --> 00:49:53.410
who don't have enough water very
soon to grow their food,

00:49:53.410 --> 00:49:56.730
could have enough water
to grow their food.

00:49:56.730 --> 00:50:00.900
The first way is that if you
build up the organic matter in

00:50:00.900 --> 00:50:04.100
your soil, you can reduce the
amount of water you need to

00:50:04.100 --> 00:50:09.110
grow food by as much as 75%.

00:50:09.110 --> 00:50:10.580
That's huge.

00:50:10.580 --> 00:50:14.340
Secondly, if you put all the
plants close together that the

00:50:14.340 --> 00:50:17.460
deep soil preparation allows
you to do, you get a

00:50:17.460 --> 00:50:19.700
mini-climate.

00:50:19.700 --> 00:50:22.260
And it shades the ground.

00:50:22.260 --> 00:50:25.180
And you can reduce the amount
of water you need by an

00:50:25.180 --> 00:50:28.770
additional up to 50% less.

00:50:28.770 --> 00:50:30.780
Now we were already
from 75% down.

00:50:30.780 --> 00:50:33.770
So we're at 25% of the water
being used because of the

00:50:33.770 --> 00:50:35.570
organic matter.

00:50:35.570 --> 00:50:38.980
So now we can get it down to
12 and 1/2% the water being

00:50:38.980 --> 00:50:43.200
used by the shading of the
ground with the mini-climate.

00:50:43.200 --> 00:50:44.880
And last, but not least--

00:50:44.880 --> 00:50:48.930
and this one is just a
mind blower to me--

00:50:48.930 --> 00:50:52.850
but I always thought plants
drank water in order to stand

00:50:52.850 --> 00:50:58.430
up and get water
turgor, right?

00:50:58.430 --> 00:51:00.420
Well, that's not untrue.

00:51:00.420 --> 00:51:05.220
But the main reason they drink
water is to get food.

00:51:05.220 --> 00:51:11.880
And if there's enough nutrients
in your soil, when

00:51:11.880 --> 00:51:15.240
they drink the water, one gulp,
and they get enough food

00:51:15.240 --> 00:51:16.220
for a long time.

00:51:16.220 --> 00:51:18.960
And they don't have to drink
more water right away.

00:51:18.960 --> 00:51:25.130
So you can then reduce by as
much as an additional 75% the

00:51:25.130 --> 00:51:26.240
amount of water you need.

00:51:26.240 --> 00:51:27.290
So you can take it down.

00:51:27.290 --> 00:51:29.320
We were at 12 and 1/2%.

00:51:29.320 --> 00:51:33.750
You can take it down to as
little as 3% of the water.

00:51:33.750 --> 00:51:36.690
And we reached that in the
Stanford Industrial Park with

00:51:36.690 --> 00:51:39.005
a crop that you'll laugh
at, zucchini.

00:51:41.780 --> 00:51:44.880
So that's how we do it.

